'''Joel Edgerton''' (born [[June 23]], [[1974]]) is an actor who played [[Owen Lars]] in the [[prequel trilogy]] and the ''[[Star Wars: Obi-Wan Kenobi]]'' television series on [[Disney+]]. He is the brother of [[Ewan McGregor]]'s stunt double, [[Nash Edgerton]], who directed his brother in the action/comedy ''Gringo'', starring [[David Oyelowo]].

Previous film roles include Gawain in 2004's ''King Arthur'', co-starring [[Keira Knightley]], [[Mads Mikkelsen]], [[Stellan Skarsgård]], and [[Ray Stevenson]].

==Biography==
Joel Edgerton was born on [[June 23]], [[1974]].<ref name="SWYT 25-06-2020" /> He portrayed [[Owen Lars]] in the [[2002]] film [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|''Star Wars'': Episode II ''Attack of the Clones'']]<ref name="AOTC">{{Film|II}}</ref> after being casted by director [[George Lucas]].<ref name="First look">{{WebCite|url=https://ew.com/tv/obi-wan-kenobi-first-look-photos|text=See exclusive first-look photos from ''Obi-Wan Kenobi''|author=Ross, Dalton|date=2022-03-09|work=''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''|archivedate=20220311122528}}</ref> He said it was the only time in his life where a dream came true that he'd never have. Edgerton was envious of his brother, [[Nash Edgerton]], because he was a stunt double for [[Ewan McGregor]] who played [[Obi-Wan Kenobi]] in the film.<ref name="Superhero Hype">{{WebCite|url=http://www.superherohype.com/news/317941-exclusive-joel-edgerton-wants-to-reprise-uncle-owen-in-star-wars|text=Exclusive: Joel Edgerton Wants to Reprise Uncle Owen in Star Wars|author=Evry, Max|date=2014-10-09|work=[http://www.superherohype.com Superhero Hype!]|archivedate=20181002001202}}</ref> While shooting ''Attack of the Clones'' in [[Tunisia]], Edgerton filmed a scene for Episode III in which he is delivered the infant [[Luke Skywalker]] by Kenobi, played by a stand-in actor, because Lucas did not desire to return to Tunisia for that single shot years later.<ref name="The Making of Star Wars Revenge of the Sith">''[[The Making of Star Wars Revenge of the Sith]]''</ref>

Edgerton also played Lars in the [[2005]] film [[Star Wars: Episode III Revenge of the Sith|''Star Wars'': Episode III ''Revenge of the Sith'']].<ref name="ROTS">{{Film|III}}</ref> The scene of Edgerton receiving the infant Luke was changed during the Episode III shoot in [[September]] [[2003]], where McGregor was filmed handing baby Luke to [[Bonnie Maree Piesse]] who played [[Beru Whitesun Lars|Beru Lars]], this time with Owen being played by an stand-in because Lucas "felt it would be better if Luke were handed over to a woman". In [[2004]], Edgerton was shot and added to the scene.<ref name="The Making of Star Wars Revenge of the Sith" />

In [[2014]], Edgerton heard about a rumored Obi-Wan Kenobi [[Star Wars Anthology Series|Anthology]] film and he expressed enthusiasm in reprising the role.<ref name="Superhero Hype" /> In [[2017]], Edgerton still wanted to reprise his role in the film and suggested that "he could go out and have some adventure and then he comes back and slips back into that unassuming [[moisture farmer]] role." Edgerton asked [[Colin Trevorrow]],<ref name="Business Insider">{{WebCite|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/joel-edgerton-star-wars-uncle-owen-2017-6|text=How Joel Edgerton plans to get back into the 'Star Wars' movies|author=Guerrasio, Jason|date=2017-06-08|work=[[Wikipedia:Business Insider|''Business Insider'']]|archivedate=20170608193608}}</ref> the filmmaker originally going to direct [[Star Wars: Episode IX The Rise of Skywalker|''Star Wars'': Episode IX ''The Rise of Skywalker'']],<ref name="Trevorrow Announced">{{SW|url=news/colin-trevorrow-to-direct-star-wars-episode-ix|text=Colin Trevorrow to Direct ''Star Wars'': Episode IX|nolive=1}}</ref> if he could return to ''[[Star Wars]]''. Trevorrow told him he had already been in ''Star Wars'' and Edgerton suggested he could play someone else such as [[Boba Fett]].<ref name="Business Insider" />

[[File:LarsFamilyBTS.png|thumb|right|180px|Joel Edgerton, Bonnie Piesse, and Grant Feely on the [[Lars homestead|Lars Homestead]] set]]
On [[March 29]], [[2021]], [[Lucasfilm]] confirmed Edgerton was a cast member of the live-action [[Disney+]] television series ''[[Star Wars: Obi-Wan Kenobi]]''.<ref name="SW">{{SW|url=news/obi-wan-kenobi-series-cast|text=''Obi-Wan Kenobi'' Series to Begin Production in April, Cast Revealed}}</ref> Director [[Deborah Chow]] was very excited to bring Edgerton and Piesse back to play Owen and Beru Lars, respectively, and she said their return was part of what made the series special.<ref name="17 year">{{WebCite|url=https://ew.com/tv/obi-wan-kenobi-ewan-mcgregor-hayden-christensen-cover-story|text=Inside the 17-year journey to reunite Ewan McGregor and Hayden Christensen for ''Obi-Wan Kenobi''|author=Ross, Dalton|date=2022-03-10|work=''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''|archivedate=20220310151626}}</ref> Edgerton and Piesse were excited to see each other again. He thought Chow was an incredible director and had a good sense of camaraderie on set.<ref name="Return">''[[Obi-Wan Kenobi: A Jedi's Return]]''</ref> [[Grant Feely]], the actor who played Luke Skywalker, made a connection with Edgerton. During filming, Chow instructed Feely how to film a certain shot and Edgerton translated the instructions into something Feely understood.<ref name="YoungEntMag">{{YouTube|video=m2EvAnPJe08|text=Interview with the new Young Luke Skywalker from Obi-Wan Kenobi|channel=@YoungEntMag|name=YoungEntMag|archivedate=20220623160216}}</ref>

